properties.pdescrip: Reconnaissance geochemistry in the Colorado Plateau, New Mexico, Colorado, Utah, and Arizona
properties.pkeyword: rare earth elements; partnerships; study areas; critical minerals; erosion; geochemistry; natural resource exploration
properties.abstract: The Colorado Plateau is part of the four corners region in New Mexico, Colorado, Utah, and Arizona, western United States and includes 36 Earth MRI focus areas covering 14 mineral systems and 38 deposit types, representing a significant geologic and mineral resource province, hosting numerous critical minerals. The New Mexico Bureau of Geology and Mineral Resources, in collaboration with the Utah Geological Survey and the Colorado Geological Survey, will have a select group of existing National Uranium Resource Evaluation (NURE) sediment pulps reanalyzed using modern geochemical methods. These sediment samples represent the best opportunity for comprehensive regional geochemistry in this area. In addition, stream sediments in select focus areas containing critical minerals will be resampled to add to our knowledge in specific areas. These data will be important for regional mineral resource assessments and general geologic studies. Potential critical minerals in the project area: barite, Co, fluorspar, Ga, Ge, Hf, Mn, Nb, Ni, PGE, REE, Sc, Ti, V, Zn, Zr.
